Scottish independent schools have a tradition of academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with another package of outstanding exam results, and additional weight is given to individual and joint successes in sport, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further education and higher education, the career they want and make them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement the above school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a favorite and preferred subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language that he understands, it goes into his head.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, it goes into his heart."
This statement is a strong reminder that we cannot only use the English language if we want to build trust and relationships with people from other countries.
The latest results of the final exams this year show that the highest scores in languages were achieved by participants of independent schools.
A total of 68% of foreign language learners received excellent grades.
Data collected at 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of pupils received an excellent grade for Mandarin, while 72% of pupils learning German, 69% of pupils learning French and 63% of pupils learning Spanish also received the highest possible grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as a key skill that children and young people will surely need in the future.
Today, languages as elective subjects are considered as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curriculum of independent schools, as well as in other places.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that 17% of employers are unable to fill jobs due to a lack of work force with language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly imperative for preparing young people for careers.
As more and more jobs require knowledge of the language, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of career choice, people who have learned to speak a foreign language in the future will feel the benefits of such a long-term skill.
A person who speaks multiple languages can communicate directly with strangers, which gives them an advantage over the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults, 75% of respondents in the UK do not speak a foreign language well enough to communicate in it, and French is the only language spoken by a bilingual percentage of respondents, or more precisely 15%.
Therefore, investing in language learning is very important for today’s children.
If children learn more languages, especially the languages of developing countries, they will have more opportunities to find good employment.
In Scotland, every school offers different languages.
Some schools will include classical, modern languages in their programme, while others will opt for languages considered to be the most important in the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of your child's interests, independent schools will always have a variety of choices, as well as teaching staff who are experts in this area.
Scottish independent schools provide an environment for children to prepare and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds for us.
We cannot ignore the fact that, in today's global business, knowledge of the language is very important for the future of each country, so it must also have an impact on education.
Thus, the knowledge of modern languages should indeed be regarded as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer language choice, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
You have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Council of Scottish Independent Schools.
