While Ri reiterated North Korea's well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "gradual" approach to denuclearization that would gradually lift sanctions on North Korea, his statement is significant because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first meeting in the history of the current US president and leader of North Korea in Singapore on June 12, when Kim vowed to work on "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula" while Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea wants to officially end the Korean War that lasted from 1950 to 1953, but the U.S. has conditioned Pyongyang to give up nuclear weapons before that.
Washington has also ignored calls for a reduction in tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on denuclearization and increases pressure with sanctions to enforce its goal, and even opposes the 'proclamation of the end of the war'," Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is just the delusion of people who know nothing about us.
The main problem is that the continuation of sanctions increases distrust."
Ri did not mention whether there are plans for a second meeting of Kim and Trump, which the US president discussed earlier this week at the United Nations.
But the minister noted that Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in had held as many as three meetings in the last five months, adding: "If denuclearization had been requested by South Korea, and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such a standstill."
Despite everything, the tone of Riy's speech differed greatly from that last year when he spoke before the UN General Assembly and said targeting the continental U.S. with missiles was inevitable after evil President Trump called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to disarm at the United Nations this year, but added that there is still a lot of work to be done and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea performs denuclearization.
