New data on the red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report of the Commission for the Conservation of Fish and the Flora and Fauna of Florida (FWC) shows a general decrease in the concentration of red tides in parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, conditions of heterogeneous algae flowering are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide stretches about 130 miles along the coast from the northern part of Pinellas County to the southern part of Lee County.
Areas of flowering can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
In the past week, average concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County or in the adjacent coastal area, low to high concentrations in the coastal area of Hillsborough County, normal to high concentrations in Manatee County, normal to high concentrations in the coastal area of Sarasota County, medium to high concentrations in the coastal area of Manatee County, medium to high concentrations in the coastal area of Sarasota County.
Cases of respiratory irritation are still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Respiratory system edema has not been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
